                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320216-246-off1396 t18320216-246-crimeloc1399"></join>. He lost from his warehouse, a pair of lamps, on Monday, the 23rd of January - they had just been japanned.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320216-246-person2058">
                  THOMAS 
                  DELANY
               <interp inst="t18320216-246-person2058" type="surname" value="DELANY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320216-246-person2058" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320216-246-person2058" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I was on duty on the 23rd of January, between three and four o'clock in the afternoon, in Short's-gardens, Drury-lane; I saw the prisoner running up Short's-gardens, and heard the cry of Stop thief! I stopped him, and found nothing on him; I asked how he came to run if he was not guilty - he said he thought the officer saw him take the lamp.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320216-246-person2059">
                  CHARLES 
                  WILKINS
               <interp inst="t18320216-246-person2059" type="surname" value="WILKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320216-246-person2059" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320216-246-person2059" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. On the afternoon of the 23rd of January, between three and four o'clock, I was in Drury-lane, and saw the prisoner at the corner of Queen-street, with this lamp - he was carrying it under his arm; he ran away, and I followed him - he threw it down in Short's-gardens; I never lost sight of him; the japan was wet on the lamp.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, stating that he had met a man named Wilson, in Queen-street, who gave him the lamp as a pattern to make one for him.</p>
